## 14. Forbidden outcomes

The implementation is noncompliant if it does any of the following:

* uses a payload width other than `u128`;
* makes zero an invalid or missing key;
* exposes key fields publicly;
* uses one untyped key struct for all structural categories;
* uses type aliases instead of distinct key types;
* permits `InPortKey<Level>` where `InPortKey<Pulse>` is required;
* permits a custom signal marker;
* infers structural category from numeric ranges or bit patterns;
* embeds category tags into the allocator payload instead of preserving category through types and variants;
* treats equal payloads in different categories as one subject;
* treats equal level and pulse payloads as one typed key;
* exposes implicit cross-category conversions;
* exposes unchecked erased-to-typed conversion;
* loses source category through `SignalSourceKey` erasure;
* omits a required erased enum;
* adds a universal `AnyStructuralKey`;
* adds `SubjectRef` or `GraphSubjectRef`;
* makes ordering depend on hash output;
* gives numeric ordering semantic meaning;
* makes hashing depend only on payload while omitting category and signal kind;
* treats Rust `Hash` output as a persisted digest;
* uses enum declaration discriminants as an undocumented canonical ordering mechanism;
* uses a single shared allocator counter for all key domains;
* allows unrelated allocation categories to perturb one another;
* uses global mutable allocation state;
* uses atomics or thread-local allocation;
* uses randomness, UUIDs, timestamps, process IDs, or memory addresses;
* claims allocator output is globally unique;
* silently wraps an exhausted counter;
* repeats a key after exhaustion;
* makes `KeyAllocator` cloneable, copyable, or default-constructible;
* exposes allocator counter mutation or reset;
* adds graph storage;
* validates key uniqueness within a graph;
* adds dense indices;
* adds resolved handles;
* adds revisions or fingerprints;
* adds persistence encoding;
* adds serialization derives;
* introduces new dependencies;
* changes existing signal or time semantics;
* creates speculative compatibility shims or placeholder future APIs.

---

## 15. Expected implementation shape

A straightforward implementation is expected to contain:

```text
private category and allocation-domain tags
small macros or shared helpers for direct key families
manual generic trait implementations where needed
typed signal-source enums
erased signal-kind enums
conversion implementations
one structured mismatch error
one caller-owned allocator
focused unit tests
compile-fail doctests
```

Macros may reduce repetition, but generated behavior must remain readable and auditable.

Avoid a macro design that obscures:

* which public types exist;
* which category tag each type uses;
* which allocator domain each type uses;
* the explicit conversion matrix;
* ordering rules;
* signal-kind distinctions.

The implementation should favor simple closed-set dispatch over speculative generic frameworks.

---

## 16. Completion criteria

This task is complete only when:

1. every required key family exists under `mossignal::key`;
2. every direct key stores one private `u128`;
3. every direct key supports explicit durable construction;
4. generic key families accept only sealed signal types;
5. structural categories remain distinct despite equal payloads;
6. level and pulse keys remain distinct despite equal payloads;
7. deterministic equality, ordering, and domain-separated hashing are implemented;
8. `SignalSourceKey<S>` preserves typed source category;
9. all seven erased enums exist;
10. erased ordering is explicit and canonical;
11. all typed-to-erased conversions exist;
12. all matching erased-to-typed conversions succeed;
13. all wrong-kind conversions return structured mismatch errors;
14. `KeyAllocator` is caller-owned and deterministic;
15. allocator payloads use namespace plus domain-local counter;
16. all sixteen allocation domains are independent;
17. exhaustion cannot wrap or repeat a key;
18. `KeyAllocator` is not cloneable, copyable, or defaultable;
19. public documentation describes the identity boundary accurately;
20. focused tests and compile-fail doctests cover the required guarantees;
21. no excluded subsystem has been started;
22. `make check-dev` passes;
23. `make check-final` passes.

The final implementation should leave the repository ready for later authored graph work without coupling stable identity to graph storage, runtime layout, global allocation, or persistence representation.
